1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4] Considered by many to be White's sharpest try for an
opening advantage and overwhelmingly the most popular first move at the
beginning to intermediate level. The great American Legend and Eleventh World
Champion when asked why he opened with 1.e4 replied "Best by test!".} e6 {
[%cal Ye7e6] What Is The French Defense?The French Defense has been referred
to as - "A Bulletproof Chess Opening For Black a chess opening for Black
versus White's 1.e4". It is characherized by the moves 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 named
after French players who used it in a correspondence match from 1834 to 1836
versus players from London.  It is considered a s very solid and resilient
chess opening played by many strong GMs of the past and present The French
Defense is one of the most trusted openings in chess, popular at all levels
from beginner to strong grandmasters.  The French Defense has been used in the
past by legendary Grandmasters Mikhail Botvinnik, Viktor Korchnoi, Tigran
Petrosian, Rafael Vaganian and Wolfgang Uhlmann.  Among the younger generation
of today's grandmasters Wesley So, Ding Liren and Alexander Morozevich all
regularly rely on the French Defense as one of their major opening weapons. 
In the French Defense, Black's 1...e6, prepares to counter the e4 pawn with 2..
.d5. Black blocks in his light-squared Bishop, but gains a solid pawn chain
and counter-attacking possibilities - generally on the queenside.} 2. d4 {
[%cal Yd2d4]} d5 {[%csl Gd5,Re4][%cal Yd7d5,Yd5e4] Black's early opening idea
in the French Defense is to establish this strong pawn on d5, thus staking a
claim to some key central light squares and attacking White's e4 pawn that he
so confidently advanced on move one!} 3. Nc3 {[%cal Yb1c3]} ({Winawer Variation
} 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3) ({Classical Variation} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4.
e5 Nfd7 5. f4) ({Tarrasch Variation - A very solid variation that has long
been the bane of the French Defense player's life. It was used with excellent
success in the 1970s by the Twelfth World Champion Anatoly Karpov and later by
the Fifteenth World Champion Viswinathan Anand.} 3. Nd2) (3. Nc3 dxe4 $5 {
Our REPERTOIRE RECOMMENDATION is to eliminate 50% of the proud white central
pawn duo and then focus on completing development and neutralizing White's
first move advantage.} 4. Nxe4 Nd7 $5 {Black prepares to follow with} (4... Nd7
) 5. -- Ngf6 {Challenging White's centralized Knight and offering to exchange
another pair of minor pieces.} (5... Ngf6 {In general, Black's plan of
development will be -} 6. -- b6 7. -- Bb7 8. -- Be7 {And in timely fashion he
will look to play the pawn break -} 9. -- c5 {Attacking the second White
center pawn.})) (3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 {We will examine several development
schemes that White may employ. But in all cases, thanks to the perserverance
of determined Black players like IM Hannes Langesrock and GM Georg Meier (2650)
, the black defenses have withstood the test of time, even against some of the
best GMs and world champions!}) *

