{In this section we will show a variation that occurs frequently at the club
level by White players who just play normal developing moves without any
special preparation.} 1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d4 {[%cal
Yd2d4]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]} 3. Nc3 {[%cal Yb1c3]} ({We can also reach our key
Rubinstein position if White wants to play the very popular Tarrasch Variation
-} 3. Nd2 dxe4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd5e4]} 4. Nxe4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd2e4]} Nd7
{[%cal Yb8d7]}) 3... dxe4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd5e4]} 4. Nxe4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal
Yc3e4]} Nd7 {[%cal Yb8d7]} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Yg1f3] Very natural, as this Knight
goes to its best square and we all know the maxim "Knights before Bishops".}
Ngf6 {[%cal Yg8f6] This Knight development was prepared by 4...Nd7 and it is
logcal to follow through with the plan of challenging White's best developed
piece - the Knight on e4!} 6. Nxf6+ {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ye4f6] Exchanging the
attacked Knight removes the tension between the two Knights.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gf6]
[%cal Yd7f6] The main point of the Nb8-d7 development was to recapture on f6
with this Knight and avoid a) Bringing the black Queen out early - 6...Qxf6 or
b) a compromised pawn structure - 6...gxf6.} (6... Qxf6) 7. Bd3 {The most
natural development for the white light square Bishop as it targets the black
h7 pawn. In the event Black castles kingside, White hopes to generate a strong
attack against the black King.} c5 $1 {This pawn break attacks what remains of
the white pawn center - the white pawn on d4. This is the key to Black
breaking out and gaining freedom and mobility for his pieces.} 8. dxc5 {
[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd4c5] As he did earlier with the Knights, White simply
exchanges the attacked d pawn.} Bxc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yf8c5] Our dark square
Bishop is able to recoup the pawn and assume control of the c5-g1 diagonal.} 9.
O-O {[%cal Ye1g1] White removes his King from the center and into safety on
the kingside.} O-O {[%cal Ye8g8] Black follows suite and removes his own King
into safety on the kingside.} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Yc1g5] White develops his last
minor piece and pins the black Knight on f6. This logical move is in fact
White's most popular continuation.} ({GM Tiviakov has tried} 10. Qe2 {[%cal
Yd1e2]} b6 {[%cal Yb7b6]} 11. Bf4 {[%cal Yc1f4] looking to take away the c7
square from the black Queen, but after} Bb7 {[%cal Yc8b7]} 12. Rad1 {[%cal
Ya1d1]} Qe7 $1 $11 {[%cal Yd8e7] Black had achieved full equality and held his
own in three high level GM encounters - Tiviakov - Vaganian 2005, Tiviakov -
Nogeiras 2008 and Caruana - Meier 2007.}) 10... b6 $1 {[%cal Yb7b6] Black
prepares to solve the "Problem of the Queen's Bishop" by fianchettoing him on
the long a8-h1 diagonal where he will be aiming at the white Knight on f3 and
pawn on g2.} 11. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2] With all of her minor pieces deployed, the
White Queen develops, connects her Rooks and vacates the desirable d1 square
for her Rooks.} Bb7 {[%cal Yc8b7] Black completes the devlopment of his last
minor piece with the completion of this fianchetto.} 12. Rad1 {[%cal Ya1d1]
The White Rook plays to the only fully open file on the board and creates
hidden threats against the black Queen -} (12. Rad1 {[%cal Ya1d1]} -- {If
White to play -} 13. Bxh7+ {[%csl Gd1,Rd8,Gh7][%cal Yd3h7,Yd1d8] A Bishop
sacrifice to unleash a discovered attack on the black Queen -} Kxh7 {[%csl Gh7]
[%cal Yg8h7]} 14. Rxd8 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Yd1d8]} Raxd8 $18 {[%csl Gd8][%cal
Ya8d8]}) 12... Qc7 $1 {[%cal Yd8c7] In view of the Bxh7 threat, the black
Queen feels compelled to step off of the d-file.  C7 is the best square for
the black Queen and note we do not fear the exchange Bxf6 gxf6, as Black
accepts doubled f-pawns, but has the Bishop Pair as compensation. In fact 13.
Bxf6 gxf6 will be examined in two of our Illustrative Games featuring former
FIDE World Champion Alexander Khalifman and a game from the youth of renowned
French Rubinstein GM Georg Meier.} ({GM Peter Acs (2526) - GM Alexander
Khalifman (2688), Dubai Rapids 2002.} 12... Qc7 {[%cal Yd8c7]} 13. Bxf6 {
[%csl Gf6][%cal Yg5f6]} gxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yg7f6] It is very important for
our understanding of the French Rubinstein, to realize this pawn structure 
(after Bxf6 gxf6) is usually not dangerous for Black. In principle, this
structure is only dangerous for Black if White can create serious attacking
chances against our black King, which is not the case here.} 14. Be4 $5 {
