[%cal Yc3e4]} Nd7 {[%cal Yb8d7]} 5. g3 {[%cal Yg2g3] This section will examine
two systems where White plays g2-g3 intending Bf1-g2 bringing his light square
Bishop to the g2-a8 long diagonal to exert pressure on the black queenside.
While the g3 systems are not considered theoretical dangerous, 5.g3 has been
White's third most popular choice and in 285 games White won 41.%, 49% were
drawn which left Black winning a measly 10%. For White, this is a quiet, low
risk approach, but if Black is prepared he should be able to neutralize
White's first move advantage.} ({Black should avoid playing "Routine, normal
moves" -} 5. g3 {[%cal Yg2g3]} Ngf6 {[%cal Yg8f6]} 6. Nxf6+ {[%csl Gf6][%cal
Ye4f6]} Nxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd7f6]} 7. Bg2 {[%cal Yf1g2]} c5 $6 {[%cal Yc7c5]
This is Black's natural central pawn break that up until now we have been
taught in general to execute as soon as possible. Howevder, in this specific
situation it plays into White's plans -} ({as now the white Bishop on g2 is
firing down the long diagonal and Black may experience some difficulty in
completing his queenside development -} 7... c5 $6 {[%csl Ra8,Rb7,Gg2][%cal
Yg2b7,Yb7a8] Therefore French Rubinstein specialists usually choose one of the
following three devlopment plans -})) ({Plan A)} 5. g3 {[%cal Yg2g3]} Ngf6 {
[%cal Yg8f6]} 6. Nxf6+ {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ye4f6]} Nxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Yd7f6]}
