1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d4 {[%cal Yd2d4]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]}
3. e5 {[%csl Rc8,Ye5][%cal Ye4e5] The Advance Variation is the most important
alternative for White to the Classical (3.Nc3) and Tarrasch (3.Nd2) variations
of the French Defense. In the 1930s it was examined in great detail by the
great Aron Nimzovich and found adherents later like Evgeny Sveshinikov in the
seventies and eighties. In modern times, super GM like Anand, Nakamura and
Grischuk enjoy success playing the white side.  With the push to e5, White
immediately gains a central space and the "Strong-Point Pawn" on e5 deprives
the black pieces of the natural d6 and f6 squares. In addition, the black
Bishop on c8 is boxed in during the early stages of the game and can become a
liability fro Black. Based on these features, White players have won many nice
attacking games of even endgames with the space advantage.  But, as often in
chess, there are pluses and minuses. On the downside, the pawn advance to e5
releases the central target and with the pawn fixed, Black can gain an early
initiative by aggresively playing to undermine the white center with pawn
moves like c7-c5 and f7-f6. This can place a burden on White to defend his
pawn chain while not falling behind in development.} c5 {[%cal Yc7c5]
Following the teachings of Aron Nimzovich, we first attack the base of the
white pawn chain and begin the process of gaining queenside space to
compensate for White's central space advantage.} 4. c3 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5]
[%cal Yc2c3] White's most popluar choice is to maintain the integrity of his
pawn chain that now runs from b2-e5.} Bd7 {[%cal Yc8d7] The system we will be
recomending is not so well known, but it is Black's third most popular choice
after 4...Nc6 and 4...Qb6. Our system is slowly gaining recognition since over
700 games, White has won 38% and Black 35% with the remaing games drawn. This
system we believe is strategically sound and even threatens to solve the long
term problem of the chronically bad light square Bishop. Once that is
accomplished Black may even have chances to fight for a strategic advantage! 
One of our heros with the black pieces who employs this system on a regular
basis is the Serbian GM Sinisa Drazic.} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Yg1f3] This natural
Knight development supports the white d4 and e5 pawns and is seen 95% of the
time.} a6 $5 {[%cal Ya7a6] Black's third most popular choice by a wide margin
after 5...Qb6 and 5...Nc6. This quiet unpretentious move has started to gain a
few followers, and will be our repetoire recomendation. In 69 games to date,
White won 36.2%,  24.6 % were drawn and Black won 39.1% !!!  One of Black's
key ideas is to play c5xd4 and meet c3xd4 with Bd7-b5 exchanging off his worst
minor pieces for one of White's best attackers!} (5... a6 {[%cal Ya7a6]} 6. Be2
{[%cal Yf1e2] White's second most popular move (After 6.Bd3) and very popular
at the club level. However, this fits in very nicely with Black's plans he has
scored very well in 38 games, Black won - 39.5% compared to White's 31.6%.}
cxd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yc5d4]} ({It is important to note the immediate attempt
to exchange our light square Bishop is tactically flawed -} 6... Bb5 $2 {
[%cal Yd7b5]} 7. Bxb5+ {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ye2b5]} axb5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ya6b5]}
