6. dxc5 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yd4c5] This capture releases the central tension
and has been White's fifth most popular choice. While not considered
theortically challenging, in practice, on the surface this seems easy system
for the White player as all of his pieces have easy development. Of course
Black is also not without pluses and the Bishop coming to c5 in one move
allows for rapid development. In fact, Black owns a crushing 60% to 27% win
ratios in the decisive games!!} Bxc5 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Yf8c5]} 7. Bd3 {[%cal
Yf1d3] White's plan is to apply a Nimzovich blockading strategy by devloping
his pieces to over-protect his e5 "Strong Point Pawn" and control the d4
square. In fighting agains this strategy, the Black moves Bd7 and a6 seems a
bit slow. However with the central position semi-blocked, Black has more than
adequate resources and in practice has scored a stunning 69% from this
position.} Ne7 $1 {This will be our repertoire recomendation!} ({But first - a
