1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d4 {[%cal Yd2d4]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]}
3. e5 {[%cal Ye4e5]} c5 {[%cal Yc7c5]} 4. c3 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Gd4,Ge5][%cal
Yc2c3] In the French Advance, over 95% of the time, White plays 4.c3 to
establish the b2-e5 pawn chain and maintain a pawn on d4 in the event Black
plays c5xd4. Nevertheless, White does have three other moves - 4.Nf3, 4.Qg4,
and 4.dxc5, which at one time or another have all been played by the great
original thinker Aron Nimzovich. Their lack of popularity is one of the main
strengths of these variations as Black players tend to be less well prepared
and thus fall into the trap of playing "routine moves'. Since White's play in
all three variations has an underlying strategic theme of allowing Black to
capture on d4 and then execute an over-protection of the e5 "Strong Point
Pawn", followed by mobilization towards a kingside attack. Black can easily
fall under the spell of White's strategic web and get crushed. However, in a
bit over 3,000 games played in all three variations combined, Black has a
small plus score.  As we will see, if Black is prepared, then it is White who
can drift into difficulties and as a rule, the longer a game goes the higher
Black's winning percentages!} (4. Nf3 {Clearly the most popular of the three
moves, but aslo the worst statistical performer of the three. In over 2500
games, White has only won 32% to Black's 49% with the rest drawn.} cxd4 5. Bd3
{The "pawn sacrifice for blockade" was the Nimzovich's idea.} ({The immediate
recapture} 5. Nxd4 {offers White less than nothing and has performed miserably
with 21% for White and 69% for Black and a few draws.}) 5... Nc6 6. O-O Nge7 7.
