4. dxc5) (4. dxc5) (4. dxc5) (4. dxc5) (4. dxc5) (4. dxc5) (4. Qg4 {A pretty
radical idea from Aron Nimzovich a White does not try to maintain his central
pawn chain and in a clear violation of basic opening principles, brings the
Queen out early before developing any Knights or Bishops! However, as they say
"There is a method to his madness" - White's plan is to over-protect the e5
Strong Point pawn and follow with moves like Nf3, Bd3, Bf4, Qg3, 0-0 and
Rf1-e1. etc. On the queenside, moves like a3 and Nb1-d2-b3 or the occasional
pawn sacrifice with c2-c3.  Under the spell of the great Nimzovich a number of
black players fell victim to White's ideas including the first Women's
Champion Vera Menchik.} Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ga5,Re1][%cal Yd8a5,Ya5e1] The great
Father Of Modern Russian Chess Mikhail Botvinnik's formative years were in the
1930s and 1940s, so he was quite familiar with Nimzovich's teaching and well
prepared when called upon to face them in 1937 against the Soviet MAster
Rabinovich. He introduced the Q check which is surprisingly disruptive to
White's plans as there is no convenient answer. Showing the general lack of
preparation against White's fourth move alterntives to c3, the Qa5+ is only
Black's fourth most popular choice even though Black has scored a crushing 69%
(!!) to White's meager 21% with a handful of draws. For those that are willing
to pick up a book and read - The 4...Qa5+ is recommended by authors IM John
Watson "Play The French" 1996 and IM Hannes Langrock "French Defense" 2018. I
absolutly agree, and this will be our REPETOIRE Recomendation!  White has
three interpositions - 5.c3. (As played against Botvinnik), 5.Nd2 (allows Nh6
attacking the white Queen with tempo), 5.Bd2 (leaving the b2 pawn undefended).
We believe Black has chances to fight for full point in all three variations!}
({Rabinovitch - Mikhail M. Botvinnik, Russia 1937.} 4... Qa5+ $1 5. c3 {
