{"If a student had time to learn only one game in the King's Indian Attack, we
would recommend this game. Fischer's play in this game became the standard to
which other games are compared!" - Karpov, Henley, Elista Diaries 1996.} 1. e4
{[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d3 {[%cal Yd2d3]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]} 3. Nd2
{[%cal Yb1d2] The knight on d2 does block in the white bishop on c1, but also
prevents Black from exchanging queens with d5xe4 and after White replies d3xe4,
Qd8xd1+.} Nf6 {[%cal Yg8f6]} 4. g3 {[%cal Yf1g2,Yg2g3] Following the KIA setup,
White prepares to fianchetto his bishop on g2.} c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5] Black
stakes his claim on the center by establishing the d5/c5 pawn duo.} 5. Bg2 {
[%cal Yf1g2]} Nc6 {[%cal Yb8c6]} 6. Ngf3 {[%cal Yg1f3]} Be7 {[%cal Yf8e7]
Black develops the last kingside piece in preparation for kingside castling.}
7. O-O {[%cal Ye1g1]} O-O {[%cal Ye8g8]} 8. e5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye5f6,Ye5d6]
White advances and establishes the e5 strong-point pawn. Note the e5 pawn
bites into the black position and deprives the black pieces use of the d6 and
f6 squares.} Nd7 {[%csl Gc6,Gd7,Re5][%cal Yc6e5,Yd7e5] The black knight
retreats from f6 and joins his teammate in attacking the white e-pawn.} 9. Re1
{[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye1e5,Yf3e5] White protects his e5 pawn and then looks to
mobilize his forces behind it.} b5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc5,Gd5] Left unchallenged on
the queenside, Black establishes a fourth rank pawn trio on d5/c5/b5 and grabs
space on the queenside.} 10. Nf1 {[%cal Yd2f1] The second white knight rotates
over to where the hoped for action is on the kingside and makes way for the
development of the c1 bishop.} b4 {[%cal Yb5b4]} 11. h4 {[%cal Yh2h4] The
h-pawn is a vital participant in White's kingside attacking plans. The advance
also makes way should the f1 or f3 knight need to use the h2 square.} a5 {
[%cal Ya7a5]} 12. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Yf4e5,Yf3e5,Ye1e5] Now we see Nimzovich
"over-protection" at work as the white pawn is only attacked twice and already
defended twice. Nimzovich advocated over-protecting valuable strong-point
pawns so in the even the opponent attempts to liquidate them, the pent up
power of the supporting pieces would be unleashed.} ({Another very good plan
for White is to advance the h-pawn -} 12. h5 $5 {as in Kamsky-Lenderman, US
Championship 2014.}) 12... a4 {[%cal Ya5a4] Black charges full steam ahead on
the queenside.  Continued development with} (12... Ba6 {[%cal Yc8a6] is also
quite logical.}) 13. a3 $1 {[%cal Ya2a3] This move was novelty introduced by
Fischer. His idea is to spend a tempo and prevent Black from playing a4-a3.
White hopes to hold Black up long enough on the queenside to force a favorable
decision on the kingside.} bxa3 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Yb4a3]} 14. bxa3 {[%csl Ga3]
[%cal Yb2a3]} Na5 $6 {[%cal Yc6a5] Black decentralizes his knight. Reasonable
alternatives suggested for Black are -} ({a)} 14... Rb8 {[%cal Ya8b8]}) ({b)} 
14... Ba6 {[%cal Yc8a6]}) ({c)} 14... Nb6 {[%cal Yd7b6]}) 15. Ne3 {[%cal Yf1e3]
} Ba6 {[%cal Yc8a6]} 16. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Yh3e6] A thematic idea in
this structure is to pressure the black e6 pawn in order to prevent him from
playing f7-f6 attempting to liquidate the white e5 strong-point pawn. Notice
this also discourages Black from trying to block up the kingside with f7-f5 as
after e5xf6 en-passant, the black pawn on e6 would again be exposed.} d4 {
[%csl Re3][%cal Yd5d4,Yd4e3] Black gains more space in the center with a gain
of tempo on the white knight, However, he also hands over the e4 square for
White use as a possible pivot point for his pieces.  Note much weaker would
have been} (16... c4 $6 {[%cal Yc5c4]} 17. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yd3d4]
after which White has a powerful grip on the center and Black would have far
less play than in the game.}) 17. Nf1 $5 {[%cal Ye3f1] Played with more
finesse than the "obvious"} (17. Ng4 {[%cal Ye3g4] as Bobby wants to use the
d1-h5 diagonal to bring his queen into the attack.  However}) (17. Ng4 {
[%cal Ye3g4]} Nb6 {[%cal Yd7b6]} 18. h5 $5 {[%cal Yh4h5] was certainly an
alternative method of conducting White's kingside attack.}) 17... Nb6 {[%cal
Yd7b6] Another Black piece moves away from the kingside.} (17... c4 $5 {
[%cal Yc5c4] would be a sharper way of fighting for the initiative at the cost
of a pawn -} 18. Nxd4 $6 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yf3d4]} (18. dxc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal
Yd3c4]} Nb6 {[%cal Yd7b6]} 19. Nxd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Yf3d4]} Nbxc4 $11 {
[%csl Gc4][%cal Yb6c4]}) 18... cxd3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Yc4d3]} 19. cxd3 {[%csl
Gd3][%cal Yc2d3]} Nc5 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4][%cal Yd8d4,Yc5d3] and White would
certainly be sidetracked from his kingside pursuits for a while.}) 18. Ng5 $5 {
[%csl Ra5,Ra6,Rb6,Gg5,Rg8][%cal Yg5f7,Yg5h7,Yg5e6,Yd1h5] The white knight on
g5 hits sensitive pawns on h7, f7 and e6, while making way for the white queen
to enter the kingside on h5.} Nd5 {[%cal Yb6d5]} ({Kicking the white knight
from g5 might prove a bit provocative -} 18... h6 $5 19. Nxf7 $6 (19. Ne4 Nd5
$13) 19... Rxf7 (19... Kxf7 $5 20. Bxe6+ Kxe6 21. Qg4+ Kf7 22. e6+ $1 Kg8 (
22... Ke8 23. Qg6+ {[%cal Yg6e8]} Rf7 24. Qxf7# {[%csl Re8,Gf7][%cal Yf7e8]})
23. Bxh6 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Yg4g7,Yh6g7]} Bf6 24. e7 Qd7 25. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 26.
Qe6+ Qxe6 27. Rxe6 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6][%cal Ye6b6,Yb6a6]}) 20. Bxe6 Qe8 21. Rb1
$16 Bd8 22. Bxf7+ Qxf7 23. e6 $40 {and White has a powerful attack. +1.90 
(FRITZ).}) 19. Bd2 {[%cal Yf4d2]} Bxg5 {After surrendering this bishop, his
dark squares around his kingside begin to suffer.} ({Again,} 19... c4 $5 {
[%cal Yc5c4] deserved consideration.}) ({Note kicking the white knight from g5
is even worse now -} 19... h6 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Yh6g5,Yh7h6]} 20. Nxe6 $1 {
[%csl Ge6][%cal Ye6d8,Ye6f8]} fxe6 21. Bxe6+ {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ye6g8,Ye6d5]} Kh7
22. Bxa5 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ya5d8]} Qxa5 23. Bxd5 $18 {and White has two extra
pawns and the safer king.}) 20. Bxg5 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Gg5][%cal Yd2g5,Yg5d8]
Bobby's Bishop Pair becomes a powerful force in his kingside attack.} ({
Also possible was creating a half-open h-file with} 20. hxg5 $5 {[%csl Gg5]
[%cal Yh4g5]}) 20... Qd7 {[%cal Yd8d7]} 21. Qh5 {[%cal Yd1h5]} Rfc8 {[%cal
Yf8c8]} 22. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Yf1d2] The White knight prepares to re-enter the
fray via the e4 pivot point (See - 16...d4 comments).} (22. Nd2 {[%csl Gd2]
[%cal Yd2e4,Ye4d6,Ye4f6]}) 22... Nc3 {[%cal Yd5c3] Black has now managed to
move all of his pieces far away from his king. Is it any wonder he has an
