1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d3 {[%cal Yd2d3] Due in large part
to historic legends like Bobby Fischer, Tigran Petrosian and Mikhail Botvinnik,
the King's Indian Attack after 1.e4 is quite popular on the amateur level. The
practical appeal is the white development scheme of d3, Nf3, g3, Bg2, 0-0 and
Nbd2 can be deployed against multiple 1.e4 defenses - the French, the Sicilian
and the Caro Kann. Part of the KIA appeal to white players they have much less
preparation work than developing different systems against each black defense.
Furthermore, in the KIA pawn structures, an understanding of typical motifs
and plans tends to be more important than memorizing specific variations.} c5 {
[%cal Yc7c5]} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Yg1f3]} b6 {[%cal Yb7b6]} 4. g3 {[%cal Yg2g3]} Bb7
{[%cal Yc8b7]} 5. Bg2 {[%cal Yf1g2]} d6 {[%cal Yd7d6]} 6. O-O {[%cal Ye1g1]}
Nf6 (6... Nf6 {For our Repertoire, we want to avoid the sharp play like we saw
in the Fischer - Myagmarsuren game where our King comes under a heavy attack.
The setup we are recomending is comparitively rare, but based on very solid
strategic play. Note also, the above position can be reached via various move
orders, but for simplicity and organizational considerations we will use the
direct French Defense move order shown here.  Black will follow with} 7. -- Be7
{[%cal Yf8e7]} 8. -- O-O {[%cal Ye8g8] and purposefully delay the development
of his queen's Knight to see whether he needs it on d7 or c6.  White has a few
different plans which we will examine and show how Black should consider
re-acting.}) (6... Nf6 {[%cal Yg8f6]} 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Yb1d2] White's most
