1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2] This move and
variation is named after the Father of Russian Chess, Mikahil Chigorin 
(1850-1908). Chigorin played this frequently in the late 1800s and won many
games, defeating great players such as Tarrasch, Rubinstein, Burn, Teichman
and Blackburne among others. It often leads to a KIA, as White often continues
with the setup - g3, Bg2, Nf3, d3 and Nbd2 etc.} (2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2]} -- 3.
g3 {[%cal Yg2g3]} -- 4. Bg2 {[%cal Yf1g2]} -- 5. Nf3 {[%cal Yg1f3]} -- 6. d3 {
[%cal Yd2d3]} -- 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Yb1d2]}) (2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2] One of the
primary points is that Black's e-pawn is now pinned so the usual 2...d5 is
nicely met by 3.exd5 Qxd5 when 3.Nc3 gives White s light lead in devlopment.}
d5 $6 {[%cal Yd7d5]} 3. exd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye4d5,Ye2e6,Ye6e8]} Qxd5 {
[%csl Gd5][%cal Yd8d5]} 4. Nc3 $32 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yb1c3,Yc3d5]}) (2. Qe2 {
[%cal Yd1e2] However, while closely akin to the KIA there are some differences
a) White can launch f2-f4 before bringing his Ng1-f3 and b) White can also
play c2-c3 and then d2-d4 in one shot, without the preliminary d2-d3. It is
also important to note that while far less popular than the KIA, White's
success ratio is considerably higher, with a very respectable White 44% to 29%
for Black. I attribute White's comparative success in the Chigorin Attack, not
to it being theoretically stronger than the KIA (If it was, Fischer would have
played it!), but rather to Black players not making it a priority to prepare
for.}) (2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2]} c5 $1 {[%cal Yc7c5] Our REPERTOIRE Recomendation
is the fluid setup beginning with 2...c5, followed by ....Nc6, ...g6, ....Bg7,
...Nge7. This is a very viable, sound and positionally solid setup against
both the Closed Sicilian and the KIA. This setup is the preferrred choice of
high level professional GMs like Sergei Dolmatov and Chinese #1 Ding Liren,
because it has stood the test of time and served Black well.} 3. -- Nc6 {
[%cal Yb8c6]} 4. -- g6 {[%cal Yg7g6]} 5. -- Bg7 {[%cal Yf8g7]} 6. -- Nge7 {
[%cal Yg8e7]}) (2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2]} c5 {[%cal Yc7c5,Yc2c3,Yg1f3,Yd2d4] White
has three basic plans -  Plan A) The KIA Plan - Continuing with typical KIA
moves like g3, Bg2, d3, 0-0, Nbd2 etcetera. Plan B) The early f4 Plan - White
plays 3. f4 followed by Nf3, 0-0, d3 and looks to build a kingside attack. 
Plan C) The d2-d4 Pawn Expansion - White plays Nf3, 0-0, c3, Rd1 (if needed)
and d4 establishing the e4/d4 central pawn duo.}) (2. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2]} c5 {
[%cal Yc7c5]} ({Jorn Snellingen (1817) - Lars Andersen (2210), Oslo Norway
