1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]} 2. d4 {[%cal Yd2d4]} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]}
3. exd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye4d5] By exchanging pawns on d5, White for no real
reason releases the central tension, which is generally the habit of weaker
players. The Exchange Variation has a reputation as being a solid and safe
riskless way for White to play. Thus it is often employed by lower rated White
players to gain a draw. However, this strategy is not without risk when we
consider the following statistics -} exd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye6d5] Black's
score in over 22,000 games is 34% wins 39% draws and only 27% losses. 
Furthermore, if we look at the scores of the three most active GMs with Black,
the statistics skew even further in Black's favor -  1) E Gleizerov  -  12
Wins, 2 losses, 28 Draws  2) Dragan Kosic -  10 Wins, 0 Losses, 29 Draws  3) W.
Uhlmann  -  15 Wins, 6 Losses, 15 Draws   However, as is typical with less
popular variations, Black must guard againts complacency and laziness. In
spite of the challenging reputation and above statistics, the Exchange
Variation is not without its own two drops of poison. First, we examine
White's most popular 4.Bd3, followed by "the two drops of poison" - 4.Nf3 and
4.c4. In all three cases, we will present our REPERTOIRE Recomendation.} (3...
exd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ye6d5]} 4. Bd3 {[%cal Yf1d3] This has not historically
scored well as Black enjoys a 33% to 25% advantage.} ({REPERTOIRE
Recomendation -} 4. Bd3 {[%cal Yf1d3]} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yb8c6,Yc6d4]
Black immediately develops a piece and attacks the white d4 pawn. This
approach has brought Black huge success with 40% Wins versus only 23% for
White! French Defense legend Wolfgang Uhlmann as well as modern day GMs
Yusupov, Kaidanov and Svedlak have used this approach. Part of the appeal is
it can often lead to "opposit side castling" where Black gets to attack on the
kingside.  If left alone, Black has a very flowing development plan in mind -}
