[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Annotator "HenleyR"]
[PlyCount "3"]

{Not a frequently seen second move, as it is White's 6th most popular choice.
However, it's relative rarity is part of its strength as it has scored a very
respectable 41% to 35% in White's favor. Part of this is probably attributable
to Black players not paying much attention to preparing specifically for
White's setup. I found that even long after I was a Master, I would be
confronted with such a system and my first thought would be "Oh this does not
look dangerous", or "This can't be any good". Then as the game would progress
I would be thinking "Hmm, White's position is not so bad" - to eventually such
thoughts as " You know, White's attack could be dangerous" or "This looks a
bit unpleasant".  White's plan in this case can be dangerous if Black follows
routine moves with slightly passive play. The leading proponent of White's 2.
b3 System is Eva Repková, a Slovak chess player holding the FIDE titles of
International Master and Woman Grandmaster. She was Czechoslovak Women's
Champion in 1991 and Slovak Women's Champion in 2003, 2010 and 2013.  Born:
January 16, 1975 (age 44 years), Stará Lubovna, Slovakia Eva's peak FIDE
rating was was 2447 in September of 2010, but her performance rating with this
system was certainly higher with 16 Wins, 7 losses and 11 draws!  Spouse: Fadi
Eid Peak rating: 2447 (September 2010)} 1. e4 {[%cal Ye2e4]} e6 {[%cal Ye7e6]}
2. b3 {[%cal Yb2b3]} ({Most French Defense Books (ie Hannes Langrock, French
Defense 2018) suggest the following repertoire for Black -} 2. b3 {[%cal Yb2b3]
} d5 {[%cal Yd7d5]} 3. Bb2 {[%cal Yc1b2]} dxe4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yd5e4]} 4. Nc3
{[%cal Yb1c3]} Nf6 {[%cal Yg8f6]} 5. Qe2 {[%cal Yd1e2]} Be7 {[%cal Yf8e7]} 6.
O-O-O {[%cal Ye1c1]} O-O {[%cal Ye8g8]} 7. Nxe4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Yc3e4] Which
is assessed as approximately equal.} {After the recommended} a5 $1 $132 {
[%csl Gb2][%cal Ya7a5,Yb2f6,Yf6g7] Black has held his own in a small sampling
of games, but I am not overly enamored of Black's position with the White b2
Bishop pointing at my King......}) ({REPERTOIRE Recomendation -} 2. b3 {
[%cal Yb2b3]} b6 $1 {"Immitation is the sincerest form of flattery"!
Recognizing a good idea, we follow suit and prepare to fianchetto our own
Queen's Bishop!} 3. Bb2 {[%cal Yc1b2]} Bb7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yc8b7,Yb7e4] White
has several options of how to respond to the early black Bishop attack on his
valuable e pawn. Not only do we look to throw White off of his routine, but
theoretically FRITZ already considers Black to have equalized! From a
practical perspective, Black has a clear 47% Wins to 38% Wins advantage!} ({A)
} 3... Bb7 {[%cal Yc8b7]} 4. e5 {[%cal Ye4e5] This advance is a bit premature
and opens the long diagonal for our light square Bishop.}) ({B)} 3... Bb7 {
[%csl Re4][%cal Yc8b7,Yb7e4]} 4. d3 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Yd2d3,Yd3e4] This pawn
advance defends the e4 pawn, but blocks in the white light square Bishop.
White has had a modest plus in practical play, but theoretically Black has
already equalized.}) ({C)} 3... Bb7 {[%csl Re4][%cal Yc8b7,Yb7e4]} 4. Nc3 {
[%csl Rb2][%cal Yb1c3] Developing a piece and defending the pawn is logical,
however it does block the long dark square diagonal for White's b2 Bishop.
While this has been White's most popular move, it has in fact brought
miserable results of only 29% White Wins versus 61% Black Wins!}) (3... Bb7 {
[%csl Re4][%cal Yc8b7,Yb7e4]} 4. Qe2 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Yd1e2,Ye2e4,Yc7c5,Yb8c6,
Yc6d4] The early Queen development defends the pawn while generally preparing
for queenside castling. However, she does block the development of her light
square Bishop and can sometimes be subject to a black Knight attack (Nb8-c6-d4)
. White has not had great success here with only 33% White Wins to 42% Black
